qText: No, I won t, I ll finish my breakfast. In fact, I haven t them. We met the Wilcoxes on an awful expedition that we made from Heidelberg to Speyer. Helen and I had got it into our heads that there was a grand old cathedral at Speyer--the Archbishop of Speyer was one of the seven electors--you know-- Speyer, Maintz, and Koln.  Those three sees once commanded the Rhine Valley and got it the name of Priest Street.
speaker: Margaret

qText: I still feel quite uneasy about this business, Margaret.
speaker: Aunt Juley

qText: The train crossed by a bridge of boats, and at first sight it looked quite fine. But oh, in five minutes we had seen the whole thing. The cathedral had been ruined, absolutely ruined, by restoration; not an inch left of the original structure. We wasted a whole day, and came across the Wilcoxes as we were eating our sandwiches in the public gardens. They too, poor things, had been taken in--they were actually stopping at Speyer--and they rather liked Helen s insisting that they must fly with us to Heidelberg. As a matter of fact, they did come on next day. We all took some drives together. They knew us well enough to ask Helen to come and see them--at least, I was asked too, but Tibby s illness prevented me, so last Monday she went alone. That s all. You know as much as I do now. It s a young man out of the unknown. She was to have come back Saturday, but put off till Monday, perhaps on account of--I don t know.

qText: And then we parted--at least, until I remembered that I had written straight off to tell you the night before, and that frightened him again. I asked him to send a telegram for me, for he knew you would be coming or something; and he tried to get hold of the motor, but Charles and Mr. Wilcox wanted it to go to the station; and Charles offered to send the telegram for me, and then I had to say that the telegram was of no consequence, for Paul said Charles might read it, and though I wrote it out several times, he always said people would suspect something. He took it himself at last, pretending that he must walk down to get cartridges, and, what with one thing and the other, it was not handed in at the post-office until too late. It was the most terrible morning. Paul disliked me more and more, and Evie talked cricket averages till I nearly screamed. I cannot think how I stood her all the other days. At last Charles and his father started for the station, and then came your telegram warning me that Aunt Juley was coming by that train, and Paul--oh, rather horrible--said that I had muddled it. But Mrs. Wilcox knew.

qText: I ve often thought about it, Helen. It s one of the most interesting things in the world. The truth is that there is a great outer life that you and I have never touched--a life in which telegrams and anger count. Personal relations, that we think supreme, are not supreme there. There love means marriage settlements, death, death duties. So far I m clear. But here my difficulty. This outer life, though obviously horrid; often seems the real one--there s grit in it. It does breed character. Do personal relations lead to sloppiness in the end?
speaker: Margaret

qText: You only care about the things that you can use, and therefore arrange them in the following order: Money, supremely useful; intellect, rather useful; imagination, of no use at all. No
speaker: Uncle Ernst

qText: your Pan-Germanism is no more imaginative than is our Imperialism over here. It is the vice of a vulgar mind to be thrilled by bigness, to think that a thousand square miles are a thousand times more wonderful than one square mile, and that a million square miles are almost the same as heaven. That is not imagination. No, it kills it. When their poets over here try to celebrate bigness they are dead at once, and naturally. Your poets too are dying, your philosophers, your musicians, to whom Europe has listened for two hundred years. Gone. Gone with the little courts that nurtured them--gone with Esterhazy and Weimar. What? What s that? Your universities? Oh yes, you have learned men, who collect more facts than do the learned men of England. They collect facts, and facts, and empires of facts. But which of them will rekindle the light within?

qText: I only care for music--a very different thing. But still I will say this for myself--I do know when I like a thing and when I don t. Some people are the same about pictures. They can go into a picture gallery--Miss Conder can--and say straight off what they feel, all round the wall. I never could do that. But music is so different from pictures, to my mind. When it comes to music I am as safe as houses, and I assure you, Tibby, I am by no means pleased by everything. There was a thing--something about a faun in French--which Helen went into ecstasies over, but I thought it most tinkling and superficial, and said so, and I held to my opinion too.
speaker: Aunt Juley

qText: So should I. Now, my sister declares they re just the same. We have great arguments over it. She says I m dense; I say she s sloppy.
speaker: Margaret

qText: Now, doesn t it seem absurd to you? What is the good of the Arts if they re interchangeable? What is the good of the ear if it tells you the same as the eye? Helen s one aim is to translate tunes into the language of painting, and pictures into the language of music. It s very ingenious, and she says several pretty things in the process, but what s gained, I d like to know? Oh, it s all rubbish, radically false. If Monet s really Debussy, and Debussy s really Monet, neither gentleman is worth his salt--that s my opinion.
speaker: Margaret

qText: Now, this very symphony that we ve just been having--she won t let it alone. She labels it with meanings from start to finish; turns it into literature. I wonder if the day will ever return when music will be treated as music. Yet I don t know. There s my brother--behind us. He treats music as music, and oh, my goodness! He makes me angrier than any one, simply furious. With him I daren t even argue.
speaker: Margaret

qText: But, of course, the real villain is Wagner. He has done more than any man in the nineteenth century towards the muddling of the arts. I do feel that music is in a very serious state just now, though extraordinarily interesting. Every now and then in history there do come these terrible geniuses, like Wagner, who stir up all the wells of thought at once. For a moment it s splendid. Such a splash as never was. But afterwards--such a lot of mud; and the wells--as it were, they communicate with each other too easily now, and not one of them will run quite clear. That s what Wagner s done.
speaker: Margaret

qText: and one must just accept it. No, Aunt Juley, I don t mean that this house is full of women. I am trying to say something much more clever. I mean that it was irrevocably feminine, even in father s time. Now I m sure you understand! Well, I ll give you another example. It ll shock you, but I don t care. Suppose Queen Victoria gave a dinner-party, and that the guests had been Leighton, Millais, Swinburne, Rossetti, Meredith, Fitzgerald, etc. Do you suppose that the atmosphere of that dinner would have been artistic? Heavens, no! The very chairs on which they sat would have seen to that. So with our house--it must be feminine, and all we can do is to see that it isn t effeminate. Just as another house that I can mention, but won t, sounded irrevocably masculine, and all its inmates can do is to see that it isn t brutal.

qText: Of course she must bow. But look here; let s do the flowers. I was going to say, the will to be interested in him has died, and what else matters? I look on that disastrous episode (over which you were so kind) as the killing of a nerve in Helen. It s dead, and she ll never be troubled with it again. The only things that matter are the things that interest one. Bowing, even calling and leaving cards, even a dinner-party--we can do all those things to the Wilcoxes, if they find it agreeable; but the other thing, the one important thing--never again. Don t you see?

qText: New for me; sensible people have acknowledged it for years. You and I and the Wilcoxes stand upon money as upon islands. It is so firm beneath our feet that we forget its very existence. It s only when we see some one near us tottering that we realise all that an independent income means. Last night, when we were talking up here round the fire, I began to think that the very soul of the world is economic, and that the lowest abyss is not the absence of love, but the absence of coin.
speaker: Margaret
menEnts: [['Aunt Juley'], ['Paul', 'Charles Wilcox', 'Mrs. Wilcox', 'Evie', 'Mr. Wilcox'], ['Margaret'], ['Margaret', 'Aunt Juley', 'Charles Wilcox', 'Paul', 'Mrs. Wilcox', 'Mr. Wilcox', 'Evie'], ['Margaret', 'Aunt Juley'], ['Margaret', 'Aunt Juley'], ['Margaret', 'Aunt Juley'], ['Margaret', 'Aunt Juley']]

qText: I call that rather cynical.
speaker: Aunt Juley

qText: So do I. But Helen and I, we ought to remember, when we are tempted to criticise others, that we are standing on these islands, and that most of the others are down below the surface of the sea. The poor cannot always reach those whom they want to love, and they can hardly ever escape from those whom they love no longer. We rich can. Imagine the tragedy last June, if Helen and Paul Wilcox had been poor people, and couldn t invoke railways and motor-cars to part them.
speaker: Margaret

qText: That s more like Socialism,
speaker: Aunt Juley

qText: Call it what you like. I call it going through life with one s hand spread open on the table. I m tired of these rich people who pretend to be poor, and think it shows a nice mind to ignore the piles of money that keep their feet above the waves. I stand each year upon six hundred pounds, and Helen upon the same, and Tibby will stand upon eight, and as fast as our pounds crumble away into the sea they are renewed--from the sea, yes, from the sea. And all our thoughts are the thoughts of six-hundred-pounders, and all our speeches; and because we don t want to steal umbrellas ourselves, we forget that below the sea people do want to steal them and do steal them sometimes, and that what s a joke up here is down there reality.
speaker: Margaret

qText: There they go--there goes Fraulein Mosebach. Really, for a German she does dress charmingly. Oh!--
speaker: Aunt Juley

qText: What is it?
speaker: Margaret

speaker: Aunt Juley

qText: Why shouldn t she?
speaker: Margaret

qText: I beg your pardon, I interrupted you. What was it you were saying about reality?
speaker: Aunt Juley

qText: I had worked round to myself, as usual,
speaker: Margaret

qText: Do tell me this, at all events. Are you for the rich or for the poor?
speaker: Aunt Juley

speaker: Margaret

qText: For riches!
speaker: Aunt Juley

qText: Yes. For riches. Money for ever!
speaker: Margaret

qText: So am I, and so, I am afraid, are most of my acquaintances at Swanage, but I am surprised that you agree with us.
speaker: Aunt Juley

speaker: Margaret

qText: Not at all, dear. I wish you would let me help you in more important things.
speaker: Aunt Juley

speaker: Margaret

speaker: Mrs. Wilcox

qText: Indeed!
speaker: Margaret

qText: We took the flat chiefly on that account, and also that Paul could get his African outfit. The flat belongs to a cousin of my husband s, and she most kindly offered it to us. So before the day came we were able to make the acquaintance of Dolly s people, which we had not yet done.
speaker: Mrs. Wilcox

speaker: Mrs. Wilcox

qText: Charles and Albert Fussell have known one another some time. They belong to the same club, and are both devoted to golf. Dolly plays golf too, though I believe not so well; and they first met in a mixed foursome. We all like her, and are very much pleased. They were married on the 11th, a few days before Paul sailed. Charles was very anxious to have his brother as best man, so he made a great point of having it on the 11th. The Fussells would have preferred it after Christmas, but they were very nice about it. There is Dolly s photograph--in that double frame.

qText: Inexperience,
speaker: Margaret

qText: Of course, I have everything to learn--absolutely everything--just as much as Helen. Life s very difficult and full of surprises. At all events, I ve got as far as that. To be humble and kind, to go straight ahead, to love people rather than pity them, to remember the submerged--well, one can t do all these things at once, worse luck, because they re so contradictory. It s then that proportion comes in--to live by proportion. Don t BEGIN with proportion. Only prigs do that. Let proportion come in as a last resource, when the better things have failed, and a deadlock--Gracious me, I ve started preaching!
speaker: Margaret

qText: Indeed, you put the difficulties of life splendidly,
speaker: Mrs. Wilcox

qText: It is just what I should have liked to say about them myself.

qText: Never,
speaker: Mrs. Wilcox
addressee: ['A Young Man Low Down In The Education Office', 'Margaret']

qText: People at Stettin drop things into boats out of overhanging warehouses. At least, our cousins do, but aren t particularly rich. The town isn t interesting, except for a clock that rolls its eyes, and the view of the Oder, which truly is something special. Oh, Mrs. Wilcox, you would love the Oder! The river, or rather rivers--there seem to be dozens of them--are intense blue, and the plain they run through an intensest green.
speaker: Margaret
addressee: ['Mrs. Wilcox', 'A Young Man Low Down In The Education Office']

qText: Indeed! That sounds like a most beautiful view, Miss Schlegel.
speaker: Mrs. Wilcox
addressee: ['A Young Man Low Down In The Education Office', 'Margaret']

qText: So I say, but Helen, who will muddle things, says no, it s like music. The course of the Oder is to be like music. It s obliged to remind her of a symphonic poem. The part by the landing-stage is in B minor, if I remember rightly, but lower down things get extremely mixed. There is a slodgy theme in several keys at once, meaning mud-banks, and another for the navigable canal, and the exit into the Baltic is in C sharp major, pianissimo.
speaker: Margaret
addressee: ['Mrs. Wilcox', 'A Young Man Low Down In The Education Office']

qText: What do the overhanging warehouses make of that?
speaker: A Young Man Low Down In The Education Office

qText: They make a great deal of it,
speaker: Margaret
addressee: ['Mrs. Wilcox', 'A Young Man Low Down In The Education Office']

qText: I think it s affectation to compare the Oder to music, and so do you, but the overhanging warehouses of Stettin take beauty seriously, which we don t, and the average Englishman doesn t, and despises all who do. Now don t say  Germans have no taste,  or I shall scream. They haven t. But--but--such a tremendous but!--they take poetry seriously. They do take poetry seriously.
speaker: Margaret
addressee: ['Mrs. Wilcox', 'A Young Man Low Down In The Education Office']

qText: Is anything gained by that?
speaker: A Young Man Low Down In The Education Office

qText: Yes, yes. The German is always on the lookout for beauty. He may miss it through stupidity, or misinterpret it, but he is always asking beauty to enter his life, and I believe that in the end it will come. At Heidelberg I met a fat veterinary surgeon whose voice broke with sobs as he repeated some mawkish poetry. So easy for me to laugh--I, who never repeat poetry, good or bad, and cannot remember one fragment of verse to thrill myself with. My blood boils--well, I m half German, so put it down to patriotism--when I listen to the tasteful contempt of the average islander for things Teutonic, whether they re Bocklin or my veterinary surgeon.  Oh, Bocklin,  they say;  he strains after beauty, he peoples Nature with gods too consciously.  Of course Bocklin strains, because he wants something--beauty and all the other intangible gifts that are floating about the world. So his landscapes don t come off, and Leader s do.
speaker: Margaret
addressee: ['Mrs. Wilcox', 'A Young Man Low Down In The Education Office']

qText: I am not sure that I agree. Do you?
speaker: A Young Man Low Down In The Education Office

qText: I think Miss Schlegel puts everything splendidly;
speaker: Mrs. Wilcox

qText: Oh, Mrs. Wilcox, say something nicer than that. It s such a snub to be told you put things splendidly.
speaker: Margaret
addressee: ['Mrs. Wilcox', 'A Young Man Low Down In The Education Office']

qText: I do not mean it as a snub. Your last speech interested me so much. Generally people do not seem quite to like Germany. I have long wanted to hear what is said on the other side.
speaker: Mrs. Wilcox
addressee: ['A Young Man Low Down In The Education Office', 'Margaret']

qText: The other side? Then you do disagree. Oh, good! Give us your side.
speaker: Margaret
addressee: ['Mrs. Wilcox', 'A Young Man Low Down In The Education Office']

qText: I have no side. But my husband
speaker: Mrs. Wilcox
addressee: ['A Young Man Low Down In The Education Office', 'Margaret']

qText: has very little faith in the Continent, and our children have all taken after him.
speaker: Mrs. Wilcox
addressee: ['A Young Man Low Down In The Education Office', 'Margaret']

qText: On what grounds? Do they feel that the Continent is in bad form?
speaker: Margaret
addressee: ['Mrs. Wilcox', 'A Young Man Low Down In The Education Office']

qText: You will admit, though, that the Continent--it seems silly to speak of  the Continent,  but really it is all more like itself than any part of it is like England. England is unique. Do have another jelly first. I was going to say that the Continent, for good or for evil, is interested in ideas. Its Literature and Art have what one might call the kink of the unseen about them, and this persists even through decadence and affectation. There is more liberty of action in England, but for liberty of thought go to bureaucratic Prussia. People will there discuss with humility vital questions that we here think ourselves too good to touch with tongs.
speaker: Margaret
addressee: ['A Girl Opposite', 'Mrs. Wilcox', 'A Young Man Low Down In The Education Office']

qText: I do not want to go to Prussia,
speaker: Mrs. Wilcox
addressee: ['A Girl Opposite', 'A Young Man Low Down In The Education Office', 'Margaret']

qText: not even to see that interesting view that you were describing. And for discussing with humility I am too old. We never discuss anything at Howards End.
speaker: Mrs. Wilcox
addressee: ['A Girl Opposite', 'A Young Man Low Down In The Education Office', 'Margaret']

qText: Then you ought to!
speaker: Margaret
addressee: ['A Girl Opposite', 'Mrs. Wilcox', 'A Young Man Low Down In The Education Office']

qText: Discussion keeps a house alive. It cannot stand by bricks and mortar alone.
speaker: Margaret
addressee: ['A Girl Opposite', 'Mrs. Wilcox', 'A Young Man Low Down In The Education Office']

qText: It cannot stand without them,
speaker: Mrs. Wilcox
addressee: ['A Girl Opposite', 'A Young Man Low Down In The Education Office', 'Margaret']

qText: It cannot stand without them, and I sometimes think--But I cannot expect your generation to agree, for even my daughter disagrees with me here.
speaker: Mrs. Wilcox
addressee: ['A Girl Opposite', 'A Young Man Low Down In The Education Office', 'Margaret']

addressee: ['A Girl Opposite', 'A Young Man Low Down In The Education Office', 'Margaret']

speaker: Margaret
addressee: ['A Girl Opposite', 'Mrs. Wilcox', 'A Young Man Low Down In The Education Office']

qText: Aren t we differing on something much wider, Mrs. Wilcox? Whether women are to remain what they have been since the dawn of history; or whether, since men have moved forward so far, they too may move forward a little now. I say they may. I would even admit a biological change.

addressee: ['A Girl Opposite', 'Mrs. Wilcox', 'A Young Man Low Down In The Education Office']

qText: I don t know, I don t know.

addressee: ['A Girl Opposite', 'A Young Man Low Down In The Education Office', 'Margaret']

speaker: A Young Man Low Down In The Education Office

qText: They ve turned disgracefully strict.
speaker: A Young Man Low Down In The Education Office

qText: Oh, but come upstairs for a little. Miss Quested plays. Do you like MacDowell? Do you mind his only having two noises? If you must really go, I ll see you out. Won t you even have coffee?
speaker: Margaret
addressee: ['A Girl Opposite', 'Mrs. Wilcox', 'A Young Man Low Down In The Education Office']

qText: What an interesting life you all lead in London!
speaker: Mrs. Wilcox

qText: No, we don t,
speaker: Margaret

qText: We lead the lives of gibbering monkeys. Mrs. Wilcox--really--We have something quiet and stable at the bottom. We really have. All my friends have. Don t pretend you enjoyed lunch, for you loathed it, but forgive me by coming again, alone, or by asking me to you.
speaker: Margaret

qText: I am used to young people,
speaker: Mrs. Wilcox

qText: I hear a great deal of chatter at home, for we, like you, entertain a great deal. With us it is more sport and politics, but--I enjoyed my lunch very much, Miss Schlegel, dear, and am not pretending, and only wish I could have joined in more. For one thing, I m not particularly well just to-day. For another, you younger people move so quickly that it dazes me. Charles is the same, Dolly the same. But we are all in the same boat, old and young. I never forget that.
speaker: Mrs. Wilcox

qText: First of all,
speaker: Margaret

speaker: Margaret

speaker: Margaret

qText: We are usually in London, and play the game with vigour--carols at the Abbey, clumsy midday meal, clumsy dinner for the maids, followed by Christmas-tree and dancing of poor children, with songs from Helen. The drawing-room does very well for that. We put the tree in the powder-closet, and draw a curtain when the candles are lighted, and with the looking-glass behind it looks quite pretty. I wish we might have a powder-closet in our next house. Of course, the tree has to be very small, and the presents don t hang on it. No; the presents reside in a sort of rocky landscape made of crumpled brown paper.

qText: Yes--that is to say, her husband wrote later on, and thanked me for being a little kind to her, and actually gave me her silver vinaigrette. Don t you think that is extraordinarily generous? He is taking up his work--rubber--it is a big business. I gather he is launching out rather. Charles is in it, too. Charles is married--a pretty little creature, but she doesn t seem wise. qText: I said,  My good Mrs. Lanoline, we have some grave misunderstanding here. Beautiful as I am, my modesty is even more remarkable than my beauty, and never, never has Mr. Lanoline rested his eyes on mine.
speaker: Helen

qText: I hope you were pleased,
speaker: Tibby

qText: Of course,
speaker: Helen

qText: A perfectly delightful experience. Oh, Mrs. Lanoline s a dear--she asked for a husband as if he were an umbrella. She mislaid him Saturday afternoon--and for a long time suffered no inconvenience. But all night, and all this morning her apprehensions grew. Breakfast didn t seem the same--no, no more did lunch, and so she strolled up to 2 Wickham Place as being the most likely place for the missing article.
speaker: Helen

qText: But how on earth--
speaker: Margaret

qText: Don t begin how on earthing.
speaker: Helen

qText: she kept repeating, not uncivilly, but with extreme gloom. In vain I asked her what she did know. Some knew what others knew, and others didn t, and then others again had better be careful. Oh dear, she was incompetent! She had a face like a silkworm, and the dining-room reeks of orris-root. We chatted pleasantly a little about husbands, and I wondered where hers was too, and advised her to go to the police. She thanked me. We agreed that Mr. Lanoline s a notty, notty man, and hasn t no business to go on the lardy-da. But I think she suspected me up to the last. Bags I writing to Aunt Juley about this. Now, Meg, remember--bags I.
speaker: Helen

qText: Likely enough,
speaker: Helen

qText: for I steal umbrellas even oftener than I hear Beethoven. Did you get it back?
speaker: Helen

qText: Yes, thank you, Miss Schlegel.

qText: The mistake arose out of my card, did it?
speaker: Margaret

qText: Yes, the mistake arose--it was a mistake.

qText: The lady who called here yesterday thought that you were calling too, and that she could find you?
speaker: Margaret

qText: That s so, calling too--a mistake.
speaker: Leonard

qText: Then why--?
speaker: Helen

qText: I said to my wife,
speaker: Leonard

qText: I said to Mrs. Bast,
speaker: Leonard

qText: and Mrs. Bast said to me,
speaker: Leonard

qText: While I was gone, however, she wanted me on important business, and thought I had come here, owing to the card, and so came after me, and I beg to tender my apologies, and hers as well, for any inconvenience we may have inadvertently caused you.
speaker: Leonard

qText: No inconvenience,
speaker: Helen

qText: but I still don t understand.
speaker: Helen

qText: I still don t understand. When did you say you paid this call?
speaker: Helen

qText: Call? What call?
speaker: Leonard

qText: This afternoon call.
speaker: Helen

qText: In the afternoon, of course!
speaker: Leonard

qText: Saturday afternoon or Sunday afternoon?
speaker: Tibby

qText: S--Saturday.
speaker: Leonard

qText: Really!
speaker: Helen

qText: and you were still calling on Sunday, when your wife came here. A long visit.
speaker: Helen

qText: I don t call that fair,
speaker: Leonard

qText: I know what you mean, and it isn t so.
speaker: Leonard

qText: Oh, don t let us mind,
speaker: Margaret

qText: It was something else,
speaker: Leonard

qText: I was somewhere else to what you think, so there!
speaker: Leonard

qText: It was good of you to come and explain,
speaker: Margaret

qText: The rest is naturally no concern of ours.
speaker: Margaret

qText: Yes, but I want--I wanted--have you ever read The Ordeal of Richard Feverel?
speaker: Leonard

qText: It s a beautiful book. I wanted to get back to the earth, don t you see, like Richard does in the end. Or have you ever read Stevenson s Prince Otto?
speaker: Leonard

qText: That s another beautiful book. You get back to the earth in that. I wanted--
speaker: Leonard

qText: I walked all the Saturday night,
speaker: Leonard

qText: I walked.
speaker: Leonard

qText: No doubt it s another beautiful book, but I d rather hear about your road.
speaker: Helen

qText: Oh, I walked.
speaker: Leonard

qText: How far?
speaker: Helen

qText: I don t know, nor for how long. It got too dark to see my watch.
speaker: Leonard

qText: Were you walking alone, may I ask?
speaker: Helen

qText: Yes,
speaker: Leonard

qText: but we d been talking it over at the office. There s been a lot of talk at the office lately about these things. The fellows there said one steers by the Pole Star, and I looked it up in the celestial atlas, but once out of doors everything gets so mixed.
speaker: Leonard

qText: Don t talk to me about the Pole Star,
speaker: Helen

qText: I know its little ways. It goes round and round, and you go round after it.
speaker: Helen

qText: Well, I lost it entirely. First of all the street lamps, then the trees, and towards morning it got cloudy.
speaker: Leonard

qText: Where did you start from?
speaker: Margaret

qText: Do tell us more.
speaker: Margaret

qText: I took the Underground to Wimbledon. As I came out of the office I said to myself,  I must have a walk once in a way. If I don t take this walk now, I shall never take it.  I had a bit of dinner at Wimbledon, and then--
speaker: Leonard

qText: But not good country there, is it?
speaker: Margaret

qText: It was gas-lamps for hours. Still, I had all the night, and being out was the great thing. I did get into woods, too, presently.
speaker: Leonard

qText: Yes, go on,
speaker: Helen

qText: You ve no idea how difficult uneven ground is when it s dark.
speaker: Leonard

qText: Did you actually go off the roads?
speaker: Helen

qText: Oh yes. I always meant to go off the roads, but the worst of it is that it s more difficult to find one s way.
speaker: Leonard

qText: Mr. Bast, you re a born adventurer,
speaker: Margaret

qText: No professional athlete would have attempted what you ve done. It s a wonder your walk didn t end in a broken neck. Whatever did your wife say?
speaker: Margaret

qText: Professional athletes never move without lanterns and compasses,
speaker: Helen

qText: Besides, they can t walk. It tires them. Go on.
speaker: Helen

qText: I felt like R. L. S. You probably remember how in Virginibus.
speaker: Leonard

qText: Yes, but the wood. This  ere wood. How did you get out of it?
speaker: Helen

qText: I managed one wood, and found a road the other side which went a good bit uphill. I rather fancy it was those North Downs, for the road went off into grass, and I got into another wood. That was awful, with gorse bushes. I did wish I d never come, but suddenly it got light--just while I seemed going under one tree. Then I found a road down to a station, and took the first train I could back to London.
speaker: Leonard

qText: But was the dawn wonderful?
speaker: Helen

qText: No.
speaker: Leonard

qText: The dawn was only grey, it was nothing to mention.
speaker: Leonard

qText: Just a grey evening turned upside down. I know.
speaker: Helen

qText: --and I was too tired to lift up my head to look at it, and so cold too. I m glad I did it, and yet at the time it bored me more than I can say. And besides--you can believe me or not as you choose--I was very hungry. That dinner at Wimbledon--I meant it to last me all night like other dinners. I never thought that walking would make such a difference. Why, when you re walking you want, as it were, a breakfast and luncheon and tea during the night as well, and I d nothing but a packet of Woodbines. Lord, I did feel bad! Looking back, it wasn t what you may call enjoyment. It was more a case of sticking to it. I did stick. I--I was determined. Oh, hang it all! what s the good--I mean, the good of living in a room for ever? There one goes on day after day, same old game, same up and down to town, until you forget there is any other game. You ought to see once in a way what s going on outside, if it s only nothing particular after all.
speaker: Leonard

qText: I should just think you ought,
speaker: Helen

qText: Curious it should all come about from reading something of Richard Jefferies.
speaker: Leonard

qText: Excuse me, Mr. Bast, but you re wrong there. It didn t. It came from something far greater.
speaker: Helen

qText: Then you don t think I was foolish?
speaker: Leonard

qText: Heavens, no!
speaker: Margaret

qText: Heaven help us if we do!
speaker: Helen

qText: I m very glad you say that. Now, my wife would never understand--not if I explained for days.
speaker: Leonard

qText: No, it wasn t foolish!
speaker: Helen

qText: You ve pushed back the boundaries; I think it splendid of you.
speaker: Helen

qText: You ve not been content to dream as we have--
speaker: Margaret

qText: Though we have walked, too--
speaker: Helen

qText: I must show you a picture upstairs--
speaker: Margaret

qText: Oh, bother, not to say dash--I had forgotten we were dining out; but do, do, come round again and have a talk.
speaker: Helen

qText: Yes, you must--do,
speaker: Margaret

qText: No, I shall not. It s better like this.
speaker: Leonard

qText: Why better?
speaker: Margaret

qText: No, it is better not to risk a second interview. I shall always look back on this talk with you as one of the finest things in my life. Really. I mean this. We can never repeat. It has done me real good, and there we had better leave it.
speaker: Leonard

qText: That s rather a sad view of life, surely.
speaker: Helen

qText: Things so often get spoiled.
speaker: Leonard

qText: I know,
speaker: Helen

qText: but people don t.
speaker: Helen

qText: Go, then; perhaps you know best; but never forget you re better than Jefferies.
speaker: Helen

qText: What s that card, eh?
speaker: Jacky

qText: Yes, don t you wish you knew what that card was?
speaker: Leonard

speaker: Jacky

qText: Well, at all events, she doesn t know about that card. Yah! done her there!

speaker: Leonard

qText: I know where you ve been, but you don t know where I ve been.
speaker: Leonard

qText: Len, I do think you might explain,
speaker: Jacky

qText: Order, order, Miss Schlegel!
speaker: The Reader Of The Paper
refExp: said the reader of the paper

qText: You are here, I understand, to advise me in the interests of the Society for the Preservation of Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty. I cannot have you speaking out of your role. It makes my poor head go round, and I think you forget that I am very ill.
speaker: The Reader Of The Paper
refExp: said the reader of the paper

qText: Your head won t go round if only you ll listen to my argument,
speaker: Margaret
addressee: ['The Reader Of The Paper', 'An Earnest Girl', 'Helen']
menEnts: [['The Reader Of The Paper'], ['The Reader Of The Paper']]

qText: Why not give him the money itself? You re supposed to have about thirty thousand a year.
speaker: Margaret
addressee: ['The Reader Of The Paper', 'An Earnest Girl', 'Helen']

qText: Have I? I thought I had a million.
speaker: The Reader Of The Paper

qText: Wasn t a million your capital? Dear me! we ought to have settled that. Still, it doesn t matter. Whatever you ve got, I order you to give as many poor men as you can three hundred a year each.
speaker: Margaret
addressee: ['The Reader Of The Paper', 'An Earnest Girl', 'Helen']
menEnts: [['The Reader Of The Paper'], ['The Reader Of The Paper'], ['The Reader Of The Paper'], ['The Reader Of The Paper']]

qText: But that would be pauperising them,
speaker: An Earnest Girl

qText: Not if you gave them so much. A big windfall would not pauperise a man. It is these little driblets, distributed among too many, that do the harm. Money s educational. It s far more educational than the things it buys.
speaker: Margaret
addressee: ['The Reader Of The Paper', 'An Earnest Girl', 'Helen']

qText: In a sense,
speaker: Margaret
addressee: ['The Reader Of The Paper', 'An Earnest Girl', 'Helen']

qText: Well, isn t the most civilized thing going, the man who has learnt to wear his income properly?
speaker: Margaret
addressee: ['The Reader Of The Paper', 'An Earnest Girl', 'Helen']

qText: Give them a chance. Give them money. Don t dole them out poetry-books and railway-tickets like babies. Give them the wherewithal to buy these things. When your Socialism comes it may be different, and we may think in terms of commodities instead of cash. Till it comes give people cash, for it is the warp of civilisation, whatever the woof may be. The imagination ought to play upon money and realise it vividly, for it s the--the second most important thing in the world. It is so slurred over and hushed up, there is so little clear thinking--oh, political economy, of course, but so few of us think clearly about our own private incomes, and admit that independent thoughts are in nine cases out of ten the result of independent means. Money: give Mr. Bast money, and don t bother about his ideals. He ll pick up those for himself.
speaker: Margaret
addressee: ['The Reader Of The Paper', 'An Earnest Girl', 'Helen']

qText: Nothing, but he would not gain his soul until he had gained a little of the world.
speaker: Margaret

qText: Cold?
speaker: Margaret

qText: No.
speaker: Helen

qText: Tired?
speaker: Margaret

qText: Doesn t matter.
speaker: Helen

qText: I say, Helen--
speaker: Margaret

qText: Well?
speaker: Helen

qText: Are we really going to follow up Mr. Bast?
speaker: Margaret

qText: I don t know.
speaker: Helen

qText: I think we won t.
speaker: Margaret

qText: As you like.
speaker: Helen

qText: It s no good, I think, unless you really mean to know people. The discussion brought that home to me. We got on well enough with him in a spirit of excitement, but think of rational intercourse. We mustn t play at friendship. No, it s no good.
speaker: Margaret

qText: There s Mrs. Lanoline, too,
speaker: Helen

qText: So dull.
speaker: Helen

qText: Just so, and possibly worse than dull.
speaker: Margaret

qText: I should like to know how he got hold of your card.
speaker: Helen

qText: But he said--something about a concert and an umbrella.
speaker: Margaret

qText: Then did the card see the wife--
speaker: Helen

qText: Helen, come to bed.
speaker: Margaret

qText: No, just a little longer, it is so beautiful. Tell me; oh yes; did you say money is the warp of the world?
speaker: Helen

qText: Yes.
speaker: Margaret

qText: Then what s the woof?
speaker: Helen

qText: Very much what one chooses,
speaker: Margaret

qText: It s something that isn t money--one can t say more.
speaker: Margaret

qText: Walking at night?
speaker: Helen

qText: Probably.
speaker: Margaret

qText: For Tibby, Oxford?
speaker: Helen

qText: It seems so.
speaker: Margaret

qText: For you?
speaker: Helen

qText: Now that we have to leave Wickham Place, I begin to think it s that. For Mrs. Wilcox it was certainly Howards End.
speaker: Margaret

qText: It is sad to suppose that places may ever be more important than people,
speaker: Margaret

qText: Why, Meg? They re so much nicer generally. I d rather think of that forester s house in Pomerania than of the fat Herr Forstmeister who lived in it.
speaker: Helen

qText: I believe we shall come to care about people less and less, Helen. The more people one knows the easier it becomes to replace them. It s one of the curses of London. I quite expect to end my life caring most for a place.
speaker: Margaret

qText: How do you do?
speaker: Henry

qText: I thought I recognised your voices. Whatever are you both doing down here?
speaker: Henry

qText: What an age it is since I ve seen you, Mr. Wilcox. I met Evie in the Tube, though, lately. I hope you have good news of your son.
speaker: Margaret

qText: Paul?
speaker: Henry

qText: Oh, Paul s all right. We had a line from Madeira. He ll be at work again by now.
speaker: Henry

qText: Ugh--
speaker: Helen

qText: I beg your pardon?
speaker: Henry

qText: Isn t the climate of Nigeria too horrible?
speaker: Helen

qText: Some one s got to go,
speaker: Henry

qText: England will never keep her trade overseas unless she is prepared to make sacrifices. Unless we get firm in West Africa, Ger--untold complications may follow. Now tell me all your news.
speaker: Henry

qText: Oh, we ve had a splendid evening,
speaker: Helen

qText: We belong to a kind of club that reads papers, Margaret and I--all women, but there is a discussion after. This evening it was on how one ought to leave one s money--whether to one s family, or to the poor, and if so how--oh, most interesting.
speaker: Helen

qText: Sounds a most original entertainment!
speaker: Henry

qText: I wish Evie would go to that sort of thing. But she hasn t the time. She s taken to breeding Aberdeen terriers--jolly little dogs.
speaker: Henry

qText: I expect we d better be doing the same, really.
speaker: Margaret

qText: We pretend we re improving ourselves, you see,
speaker: Helen

qText: We suppose it a good thing to waste an evening once a fortnight over a debate, but, as my sister says, it may be better to breed dogs.
speaker: Helen

qText: Not at all. I don t agree with your sister. There s nothing like a debate to teach one quickness. I often wish I had gone in for them when I was a youngster. It would have helped me no end.
speaker: Henry

qText: Quickness--?
speaker: Helen

qText: Yes. Quickness in argument. Time after time I ve missed scoring a point because the other man has had the gift of the gab and I haven t. Oh, I believe in these discussions.
speaker: Henry

qText: Oh yes, it doesn t much matter what subject you take,
speaker: Henry

qText: But this is going to be far better than the debate itself.
speaker: Margaret

qText: No, I won t go on,
speaker: Helen

qText: I ll just put our special case to Mr. Wilcox.
speaker: Helen

qText: About Mr. Bast? Yes, do. He ll be more lenient to a special case.
speaker: Margaret

qText: But, Mr. Wilcox, do first light another cigarette. It s this. We ve just come across a young fellow, who s evidently very poor, and who seems interest--
speaker: Helen

qText: What s his profession?
speaker: Henry

qText: Clerk.
speaker: Helen

qText: What in?
speaker: Henry

qText: Do you remember, Margaret?
speaker: Helen

qText: Porphyrion Fire Insurance Company.
speaker: Margaret

qText: Oh yes; the nice people who gave Aunt Juley a new hearth rug. He seems interesting, in some ways very, and one wishes one could help him. He is married to a wife whom he doesn t seem to care for much. He likes books, and what one may roughly call adventure, and if he had a chance--But he is so poor. He lives a life where all the money is apt to go on nonsense and clothes. One is so afraid that circumstances will be too strong for him and that he will sink. Well, he got mixed up in our debate. He wasn t the subject of it, but it seemed to bear on his point. Suppose a millionaire died, and desired to leave money to help such a man. How should he be helped? Should he be given three hundred pounds a year direct, which was Margaret s plan? Most of them thought this would pauperise him. Should he and those like him be given free libraries? I said  No!  He doesn t want more books to read, but to read books rightly. My suggestion was he should be given something every year towards a summer holiday, but then there is his wife, and they said she would have to go too. Nothing seemed quite right! Now what do you think? Imagine that you were a millionaire, and wanted to help the poor. What would you do?
speaker: Helen

qText: My dear Miss Schlegel, I will not rush in where your sex has been unable to tread. I will not add another plan to the numerous excellent ones that have been already suggested. My only contribution is this: let your young friend clear out of the Porphyrion Fire Insurance Company with all possible speed.
speaker: Henry

qText: Why?
speaker: Margaret

qText: This is between friends. It ll be in the Receiver s hands before Christmas. It ll smash,
speaker: Henry

qText: Dear me, Helen, listen to that. And he ll have to get another place!
speaker: Margaret

qText: WILL have? Let him leave the ship before it sinks. Let him get one now.
speaker: Henry

qText: Rather than wait, to make sure?
speaker: Margaret

qText: Decidedly.
speaker: Henry

qText: Why s that?
speaker: Margaret

qText: Naturally the man who s in a situation when he applies stands a better chance, is in a stronger position, that the man who isn t. It looks as if he s worth something. I know by myself--(this is letting you into the State secrets)--it affects an employer greatly. Human nature, I m afraid.
speaker: Henry

qText: I hadn t thought of that,
speaker: Margaret

qText: Our human nature appears to be the other way round. We employ people because they re unemployed. The boot man, for instance.
speaker: Helen

qText: And how does he clean the boots?
speaker: Henry

qText: Not well,
speaker: Margaret

qText: There you are!
speaker: Henry

qText: Then do you really advise us to tell this youth--?
speaker: Margaret

qText: I advise nothing,
speaker: Henry

qText: I oughtn t to have spoken--but I happen to know, being more or less behind the scenes. The Porphyrion s a bad, bad concern--Now, don t say I said so. It s outside the Tariff Ring.
speaker: Henry

qText: Certainly I won t say. In fact, I don t know what that means.
speaker: Margaret

qText: I thought an insurance company never smashed,
speaker: Helen

qText: Don t the others always run in and save them?
speaker: Helen

qText: You re thinking of reinsurance,
speaker: Henry

qText: It is exactly there that the Porphyrion is weak. It has tried to undercut, has been badly hit by a long series of small fires, and it hasn t been able to reinsure. I m afraid that public companies don t save one another for love.
speaker: Henry

qText: Human nature,  I suppose,
speaker: Helen

qText: Yes, extremely,
speaker: Henry

qText: And how s Howards End looking?
speaker: Margaret

qText: It s let.
speaker: Henry

qText: Really. And you wandering homeless in longhaired Chelsea? How strange are the ways of Fate!
speaker: Margaret

qText: No; it s let unfurnished. We ve moved.
speaker: Henry

qText: Why, I thought of you both as anchored there for ever. Evie never told me.
speaker: Margaret

qText: I dare say when you met Evie the thing wasn t settled. We only moved a week ago. Paul has rather a feeling for the old place, and we held on for him to have his holiday there; but, really, it is impossibly small. Endless drawbacks. I forget whether you ve been up to it?
speaker: Henry

qText: As far as the house, never.
speaker: Margaret

qText: Well, Howards End is one of those converted farms. They don t really do, spend what you will on them. We messed away with a garage all among the wych-elm roots, and last year we enclosed a bit of the meadow and attempted a rockery. Evie got rather keen on Alpine plants. But it didn t do--no, it didn t do. You remember, your sister will remember, the farm with those abominable guinea-fowls, and the hedge that the old woman never would cut properly, so that it all went thin at the bottom. And, inside the house, the beams--and the staircase through a door--picturesque enough, but not a place to live in.
speaker: Henry

qText: Full tide. And the position wasn t right either. The neighbourhood s getting suburban. Either be in London or out of it, I say; so we ve taken a house in Ducie Street, close to Sloane Street, and a place right down in Shropshire--Oniton Grange. Ever heard of Oniton? Do come and see us--right away from everywhere, up towards Wales.
speaker: Henry

qText: What a change!
speaker: Margaret

qText: I can t imagine Howards End or Hilton without you.
speaker: Margaret

qText: Hilton isn t without us,
speaker: Henry

qText: Charles is there still.
speaker: Henry

qText: Still?
speaker: Margaret

qText: But I thought he was still at Epsom. They were furnishing that Christmas--one Christmas. How everything alters! I used to admire Mrs. Charles from our windows very often. Wasn t it Epsom?
speaker: Margaret

qText: Yes, but they moved eighteen months ago. Charles, the good chap
speaker: Henry

qText: thought I should be lonely. I didn t want him to move, but he would, and took a house at the other end of Hilton, down by the Six Hills. He had a motor, too. There they all are, a very jolly party--he and she and the two grandchildren.
speaker: Henry

qText: I manage other people s affairs so much better than they manage them themselves,
speaker: Margaret

qText: When you moved out of Howards End, I should have moved Mr. Charles Wilcox into it. I should have kept so remarkable a place in the family.
speaker: Margaret

qText: So it is,
speaker: Henry

qText: I haven t sold it, and don t mean to.
speaker: Henry

qText: No; but none of you are there.

qText: Oh, we ve got a splendid tenant--Hamar Bryce, an invalid. If Charles ever wanted it--but he won t. Dolly is so dependent on modern conveniences. No, we have all decided against Howards End. qText: Bungle, my dear! You are too little to recollect--in fact, you weren t there. speaker: Tibby

qText: Remember that I am cosmopolitan, please.
speaker: Tibby

qText: Helen may be right.
speaker: Margaret

qText: Of course she s right,
speaker: Helen

qText: This is awfully kind of you,
speaker: Margaret

qText: but I m afraid it s not going to do. The house has not been built that suits the Schlegel family.
speaker: Margaret

qText: What! Have you come up determined not to deal?
speaker: Henry

qText: Not exactly.
speaker: Margaret

qText: Not exactly? In that case let s be starting.
speaker: Henry

qText: Presumably it s very beautiful,
speaker: Margaret

qText: How do you like it, Crane?
speaker: Margaret

qText: Come, let s be starting,
speaker: Henry

qText: How on earth did you know that my chauffeur was called Crane?
speaker: Henry

qText: Why, I know Crane; I ve been for a drive with Evie once. I know that you ve got a parlourmaid called Milton. I know all sorts of things.
speaker: Margaret

qText: Evie!
speaker: Henry

qText: You won t see her. She s gone out with Cahill. It s no fun, I can tell you, being left so much alone. I ve got my work all day--indeed, a great deal too much of it--but when I come home in the evening, I tell you, I can t stand the house.
speaker: Henry

qText: In my absurd way, I m lonely too,
speaker: Margaret

qText: It s heart-breaking to leave one s old home. I scarcely remember anything before Wickham Place, and Helen and Tibby were born there. Helen says--
speaker: Margaret

qText: You, too, feel lonely?
speaker: Henry

qText: Horribly. Hullo, Parliament s back!
speaker: Margaret

qText: Yes, they are talking again,
speaker: Henry

qText: But you were going to say--
speaker: Henry

qText: Only some rubbish about furniture. Helen says it alone endures while men and houses perish, and that in the end the world will be a desert of chairs and sofas--just imagine it!--rolling through infinity with no one to sit upon them.
speaker: Margaret

qText: Your sister always likes her little joke.
speaker: Henry

qText: She says  Yes,  my brother says `No,  to Ducie Street. It s no fun helping us, Mr. Wilcox, I assure you.
speaker: Margaret

qText: You are not as unpractical as you pretend. I shall never believe it.
speaker: Henry

qText: At all events you responded to my telegram promptly,
speaker: Henry

qText: Oh, even I know a good thing when I see it.
speaker: Margaret

qText: I m glad you don t despise the goods of this world.
speaker: Henry

qText: Heavens, no! Only idiots and prigs do that.
speaker: Margaret

qText: I am glad, very glad,
speaker: Henry

qText: There is so much cant talked in would-be intellectual circles. I am glad you don t share it. Self-denial is all very well as a means of strengthening the character. But I can t stand those people who run down comforts. They have usually some axe to grind. Can you?
speaker: Henry

qText: Comforts are of two kinds,
speaker: Margaret

qText: those we can share with others, like fire, weather, or music; and those we can t--food, food, for instance. It depends.
speaker: Margaret

qText: I mean reasonable comforts, of course. I shouldn t like to think that you--
speaker: Henry

qText: I want to go over the whole house,
speaker: Margaret

qText: As soon as I get back to Swanage, which will be to-morrow afternoon, I ll talk it over once more with Helen and Tibby, and wire you  yes  or  no.
speaker: Margaret

qText: Right. The dining-room.
speaker: Henry

qText: Now the entrance-hall.
speaker: Henry

qText: Here we fellows smoke.
speaker: Henry

qText: Oh, jolly!
speaker: Margaret

qText: You do like it?
speaker: Henry

qText: It s all rubbish not making oneself comfortable. Isn t it?
speaker: Henry

qText: Ye--es. Semi-rubbish. Are those Cruikshanks?
speaker: Margaret

qText: Gillrays. Shall we go on upstairs?
speaker: Henry

qText: Does all this furniture come from Howards End?
speaker: Margaret

qText: The Howards End furniture has all gone to Oniton.
speaker: Henry

qText: Does--However, I m concerned with the house, not the furniture. How big is this smoking-room?
speaker: Margaret

qText: Thirty by fifteen. No, wait a minute. Fifteen and a half.
speaker: Henry

qText: Ah, well. Mr. Wilcox, aren t you ever amused at the solemnity with which we middle classes approach the subject of houses?
speaker: Margaret

qText: Miss Schlegel
speaker: Henry

qText: I have had you up on false pretences. I want to speak about a much more serious matter than a house.
speaker: Henry

qText: Could you be induced to share my--is it probable--
speaker: Henry

qText: Oh, Mr. Wilcox!
speaker: Margaret

qText: I see, I see. I will write to you afterwards if I may.
speaker: Margaret

qText: Miss Schlegel--Margaret you don t understand.
speaker: Henry

qText: Oh yes! Indeed, yes!
speaker: Margaret

qText: I am asking you to be my wife.
speaker: Henry

qText: You aren t offended, Miss Schlegel?
speaker: Henry

qText: How could I be offended?
speaker: Margaret

qText: Good-bye,
speaker: Margaret

qText: You will have a letter from me--I am going back to Swanage to-morrow.
speaker: Margaret

qText: Thank you.
speaker: Henry

qText: Good-bye, and it s you I thank.
speaker: Margaret

qText: I may order the motor round, mayn t I?
speaker: Henry

qText: That would be most kind.
speaker: Margaret

qText: I wish I had written. Ought I to have written?
speaker: Henry

qText: Not at all.
speaker: Margaret

qText: There s just one question--
speaker: Henry

qText: And your English lakes--Vindermere, Grasmere they, then, unhealthy?
speaker: Frieda

qText: No, Frau Liesecke; but that is because they are fresh water, and different. Salt water ought to have tides, and go up and down a great deal, or else it smells. Look, for instance, at an aquarium.
speaker: Aunt Juley

qText: An aquarium! Oh, MEESIS Munt, you mean to tell me that fresh aquariums stink less than salt? Why, then Victor, my brother-in-law, collected many tadpoles--
speaker: Frieda

qText: You are not to say  stink,
speaker: Helen

qText: at least, you may say it, but you must pretend you are being funny while you say it.
speaker: Helen

qText: Then  smell.  And the mud of your Pool down there--does it not smell, or may I say  stink,  ha, ha?
speaker: Frieda

qText: There always has been mud in Poole Harbour,
speaker: Aunt Juley

qText: The rivers bring it down, and a most valuable oyster-fishery depends upon it.
speaker: Aunt Juley

qText: Yes, that is so,
speaker: Frieda

qText: Bournemouth is,
speaker: Aunt Juley

qText: Bournemouth is, Poole was, and Swanage is to be the most important town of all and biggest of the three.  Now, Frau Liesecke, I have shown you Bournemouth, and I have shown you Poole, so let us walk backward a little, and look down again at Swanage.
speaker: Aunt Juley

qText: Aunt Juley, wouldn t that be Meg s train?
speaker: Helen

qText: Oh, dearest Margaret, I do hope she won t be overtired.
speaker: Aunt Juley

qText: Oh, I do wonder--I do wonder whether she s taken the house.
speaker: Helen

qText: I hope she hasn t been hasty.
speaker: Aunt Juley

qText: So do I--oh, SO do I.
speaker: Helen

qText: Will it be as beautiful as Wickham Place?
speaker: Frieda

qText: I should think it would. Trust Mr. Wilcox for doing himself proud. All those Ducie Street houses are beautiful in their modern way, and I can t think why he doesn t keep on with it. But it s really for Evie that he went there, and now that Evie s going to be married--
speaker: Helen

qText: Ah!
speaker: Frieda

qText: You ve never seen Miss Wilcox, Frieda. How absurdly matrimonial you are!
speaker: Helen

qText: But sister to that Paul?
speaker: Frieda

qText: Yes.
speaker: Helen

qText: And to that Charles,
speaker: Aunt Juley

qText: Oh, Helen, Helen, what a time that was!
speaker: Aunt Juley

qText: Meg and I haven t got such tender hearts. If there s a chance of a cheap house, we go for it.
speaker: Helen

qText: Now look, Frau Liesecke, at my niece s train. You see, it is coming towards us--coming, coming; and, when it gets to Corfe, it will actually go THROUGH the downs, on which we are standing, so that, if we walk over, as I suggested, and look down on Swanage, we shall see it coming on the other side. Shall we?
speaker: Aunt Juley

qText: You see,
speaker: Helen

qText: the Wilcoxes collect houses as your Victor collects tadpoles. They have, one, Ducie Street; two, Howards End, where my great rumpus was; three, a country seat in Shropshire; four, Charles has a house in Hilton; and five, another near Epsom; and six, Evie will have a house when she marries, and probably a pied-a-terre in the country--which makes seven. Oh yes, and Paul a hut in Africa makes eight. I wish we could get Howards End. That was something like a dear little house! Didn t you think so, Aunt Juley?
speaker: Helen

qText: I had too much to do, dear, to look at it,
speaker: Aunt Juley

qText: I had everything to settle and explain, and Charles Wilcox to keep in his place besides. It isn t likely I should remember much. I just remember having lunch in your bedroom.
speaker: Aunt Juley

qText: Yes, so do I. But, oh dear, dear, how dreadful it all seems! And in the autumn there began that anti-Pauline movement--you, and Frieda, and Meg, and Mrs. Wilcox, all obsessed with the idea that I might yet marry Paul.
speaker: Helen

qText: You yet may,
speaker: Frieda

qText: The Great Wilcox Peril will never return. If I m certain of anything it s of that.
speaker: Helen

qText: One is certain of nothing but the truth of one s own emotions.
speaker: Frieda

qText: Look!
speaker: Aunt Juley

qText: Stand where I stand, and you will see the pony-cart coming. I see the pony-cart coming.
speaker: Aunt Juley

qText: Have you got the house?
speaker: Helen

qText: Oh, what a nuisance! So we re as we were?
speaker: Helen

qText: Not exactly.
speaker: Margaret

qText: Some mystery,
speaker: Tibby

qText: We are to be enlightened presently.
speaker: Tibby

qText: It s just like a widower,
speaker: Helen

qText: They ve cheek enough for anything, and invariably select one of their first wife s friends.
speaker: Helen

qText: That type--
speaker: Helen

qText: Meg, not anything wrong with you?
speaker: Helen

qText: Wait one minute,
speaker: Margaret

qText: But you ve never conceivably--you ve never--
speaker: Helen

qText: Tibby, hurry up through; I can t hold this gate indefinitely. Aunt Juley! I say, Aunt Juley, make the tea, will you, and Frieda; we ve got to talk houses, and will come on afterwards.
speaker: Helen

qText: Oh, really--
speaker: Margaret

qText: Don t,
speaker: Helen

qText: don t, don t, Meg, don t!
speaker: Helen

qText: Don t, don t do such a thing! I tell you not to--don t! I know--don t!
speaker: Helen

qText: What do you know?
speaker: Margaret

qText: Panic and emptiness,
speaker: Helen

qText: Don t!
speaker: Helen

qText: Helen is a little selfish. I have never behaved like this when there has seemed a chance of her marrying.
speaker: Margaret

qText: But we would still see each other very--often, and you--
speaker: Margaret

qText: It s not a thing like that,
speaker: Helen

qText: What s happened to you?
speaker: Margaret

qText: But it s stupid!
speaker: Helen

qText: I don t know what s happened to either of us,
speaker: Margaret

qText: We must both have gone mad.
speaker: Margaret

qText: Look here, sit down.
speaker: Margaret

qText: All right; I ll sit down if you ll sit down.
speaker: Helen

qText: There.
speaker: Margaret

qText: Now, whatever, whatever is the matter?
speaker: Margaret

qText: I do mean what I said. Don t; it wouldn t do.
speaker: Helen

qText: Oh, Helen, stop saying  don t ! It s ignorant. It s as if your head wasn t out of the slime.  Don t  is probably what Mrs. Bast says all the day to Mr. Bast.
speaker: Margaret

qText: Well?
speaker: Margaret

qText: Tell me about it first, and meanwhile perhaps I ll have got my head out of the slime.
speaker: Helen

qText: That s better. Well, where shall I begin? When I arrived at Waterloo--no, I ll go back before that, because I m anxious you should know everything from the first. The  first  was about ten days ago. It was the day Mr. Bast came to tea and lost his temper. I was defending him, and Mr. Wilcox became jealous about me, however slightly. I thought it was the involuntary thing, which men can t help any more than we can. You know--at least, I know in my own case--when a man has said to me,  So-and-so s a pretty girl,  I am seized with a momentary sourness against So-and-so, and long to tweak her ear. It s a tiresome feeling, but not an important one, and one easily manages it. But it wasn t only this in Mr. Wilcox s case, I gather now.
speaker: Margaret

qText: Then you love him?
speaker: Helen

qText: It is wonderful knowing that a real man cares for you,
speaker: Margaret

qText: The mere fact of that grows more tremendous. Remember, I ve known and liked him steadily for nearly three years.
speaker: Margaret

qText: But loved him?
speaker: Helen

qText: No.
speaker: Margaret

qText: But you will?
speaker: Helen

qText: Yes,
speaker: Margaret

qText: of that I m pretty sure. Indeed, I began the moment he spoke to me.
speaker: Margaret

qText: And have settled to marry him?
speaker: Helen

qText: I had, but am wanting a long talk about it now. What is it against him, Helen? You must try and say.
speaker: Margaret

qText: It is ever since Paul,
speaker: Helen

qText: But what has Mr. Wilcox to do with Paul?
speaker: Margaret

qText: But he was there, they were all there that morning when I came down to breakfast, and saw that Paul was frightened--the man who loved me frightened and all his paraphernalia fallen, so that I knew it was impossible, because personal relations are the important thing for ever and ever, and not this outer life of telegrams and anger.
speaker: Helen

qText: That s foolish. In the first place, I disagree about the outer life. Well, we ve often argued that. The real point is that there is the widest gulf between my love-making and yours. Yours was romance; mine will be prose. I m not running it down--a very good kind of prose, but well considered, well thought out. For instance, I know all Mr. Wilcox s faults. He s afraid of emotion. He cares too much about success, too little about the past. His sympathy lacks poetry, and so isn t sympathy really. I d even say
speaker: Margaret

qText: that, spiritually, he s not as honest as I am. Doesn t that satisfy you?
speaker: Margaret

qText: No, it doesn t,
speaker: Helen

qText: It makes me feel worse and worse. You must be mad.
speaker: Helen

qText: I don t intend him, or any man or any woman, to be all my life--good heavens, no! There are heaps of things in me that he doesn t, and shall never, understand.
speaker: Margaret

qText: So with him,
speaker: Margaret

qText: There are heaps of things in him--more especially things that he does that will always be hidden from me. He has all those public qualities which you so despise and which enable all this--
speaker: Margaret

qText: If Wilcoxes hadn t worked and died in England for thousands of years, you and I couldn t sit here without having our throats cut. There would be no trains, no ships to carry us literary people about in, no fields even. Just savagery. No--perhaps not even that. Without their spirit life might never have moved out of protoplasm. More and more do I refuse to draw my income and sneer at those who guarantee it. There are times when it seems to me--
speaker: Margaret

qText: And to me, and to all women. So one kissed Paul.
speaker: Helen

qText: That s brutal,
speaker: Margaret

qText: Mine is an absolutely different case. I ve thought things out.
speaker: Margaret

qText: It makes no difference thinking things out. They come to the same.
speaker: Helen

qText: Rubbish!
speaker: Margaret

qText: One would lose something,
speaker: Helen

qText: Do you remember the Embankment at Chelsea? It can t be ten days ago.
speaker: Margaret

qText: Yes,
speaker: Henry

qText: And you and your sister were head and ears deep in some Quixotic scheme. Ah well!
speaker: Henry

qText: I little thought then, certainly. Did you?
speaker: Margaret

qText: I don t know about that; I shouldn t like to say.
speaker: Henry

qText: Why, was it earlier?
speaker: Margaret

qText: Did you think of me this way earlier! How extraordinarily interesting, Henry! Tell me.
speaker: Margaret

qText: I didn t think of it,
speaker: Margaret

qText: No; when you spoke to me in the drawing-room, that was practically the first. It was all so different from what it s supposed to be. On the stage, or in books, a proposal is--how shall I put it?--a full-blown affair, a kind of bouquet; it loses its literal meaning. But in life a proposal really is a proposal--
speaker: Margaret

qText: By the way--
speaker: Henry

qText: --a suggestion, a seed,
speaker: Margaret

qText: I was thinking, if you didn t mind, that we ought to spend this evening in a business talk; there will be so much to settle.
speaker: Henry

qText: I think so too.  Tell me, in the first place, how did you get on with Tibby?
speaker: Margaret

qText: With your brother?
speaker: Henry

qText: Yes, during cigarettes.
speaker: Margaret

qText: Oh, very well.
speaker: Henry

qText: I am so glad,
speaker: Margaret

qText: What did you talk about? Me, presumably.
speaker: Margaret

qText: About Greece too.
speaker: Henry

qText: Greece was a very good card, Henry. Tibby s only a boy still, and one has to pick and choose subjects a little. Well done.
speaker: Margaret

qText: I was telling him I have shares in a currant-farm near Calamata.
speaker: Henry

qText: What a delightful thing to have shares in! Can t we go there for our honeymoon?
speaker: Margaret

qText: What to do?
speaker: Henry

qText: To eat the currants. And isn t there marvellous scenery?
speaker: Margaret

qText: Moderately, but it s not the kind of place one could possibly go to with a lady.
speaker: Henry

qText: Why not?
speaker: Margaret

qText: No hotels.
speaker: Henry

qText: Some ladies do without hotels. Are you aware that Helen and I have walked alone over the Apennines, with our luggage on our backs?
speaker: Margaret

qText: I wasn t aware, and, if I can manage it, you will never do such a thing again.
speaker: Henry

qText: You haven t found time for a talk with Helen yet, I suppose?
speaker: Margaret

qText: No.
speaker: Henry

qText: Do, before you go. I am so anxious you two should be friends.
speaker: Margaret

qText: Your sister and I have always hit it off,
speaker: Henry

qText: But we re drifting away from our business. Let me begin at the beginning. You know that Evie is going to marry Percy Cahill.
speaker: Henry

qText: Dolly s uncle.
speaker: Margaret

qText: Exactly. The girl s madly in love with him. A very good sort of fellow, but he demands--and rightly--a suitable provision with her. And in the second place you will naturally understand, there is Charles. Before leaving town, I wrote Charles a very careful letter. You see, he has an increasing family and increasing expenses, and the I. and W. A. is nothing particular just now, though capable of development.
speaker: Henry

qText: Poor fellow!
speaker: Margaret

qText: Charles being the elder son, some day Charles will have Howards End; but I am anxious, in my own happiness, not to be unjust to others.
speaker: Henry

qText: Of course not,
speaker: Margaret

qText: you mean money. How stupid I am! Of course not!
speaker: Margaret

qText: Yes, Money, since you put it so frankly. I am determined to be just to all--just to you, just to them. I am determined that my children shall have me.
speaker: Henry

qText: Be generous to them,
speaker: Margaret

qText: Bother justice!
speaker: Margaret

qText: I am determined--and have already written to Charles to that effect--
speaker: Henry

qText: But how much have you got?
speaker: Margaret

qText: What?
speaker: Henry

qText: How much have you a year? I ve six hundred.
speaker: Margaret

qText: My income?
speaker: Henry

qText: Yes. We must begin with how much you have, before we can settle how much you can give Charles. Justice, and even generosity, depend on that.
speaker: Margaret

qText: I must say you re a downright young woman,
speaker: Henry

qText: What a question to spring on a fellow!
speaker: Henry

qText: Don t you know your income? Or don t you want to tell it me?
speaker: Margaret

qText: That s all right
speaker: Margaret

qText: don t tell me. I don t want to know. I can do the sum just as well by proportion. Divide your income into ten parts. How many parts would you give to Evie, how many to Charles, how many to Paul?
speaker: Margaret

qText: The fact is, my dear, I hadn t any intention of bothering you with details. I only wanted to let you know that--well, that something must be done for the others, and you ve understood me perfectly, so let s pass on to the next point.
speaker: Henry

qText: Yes, we ve settled that,
speaker: Margaret

qText: Go ahead; give away all you can, bearing in mind that I ve a clear six hundred. What a mercy it is to have all this money about one.
speaker: Margaret

qText: We ve none too much, I assure you; you re marrying a poor man.
speaker: Henry

qText: Helen wouldn t agree with me here,
speaker: Margaret

qText: Helen daren t slang the rich, being rich herself, but she would like to. There s an odd notion, that I haven t yet got hold of, running about at the back of her brain, that poverty is somehow  real.  She dislikes all organisation, and probably confuses wealth with the technique of wealth. Sovereigns in a stocking wouldn t bother her; cheques do. Helen is too relentless. One can t deal in her high-handed manner with the world.
speaker: Margaret

qText: There s this other point, and then I must go back to my hotel and write some letters. What s to be done now about the house in Ducie Street?
speaker: Henry

qText: Keep it on--at least, it depends. When do you want to marry me?
speaker: Margaret

qText: I say!
speaker: Henry
refExp: Mr Wilcox turned on them and said

qText: Take care I don t report you to the police.
speaker: Henry
refExp: Mr Wilcox turned on them and said

qText: Evie will probably be married in September. We could scarcely think of anything before then.
speaker: Henry

qText: The earlier the nicer, Henry. Females are not supposed to say such things, but the earlier the nicer.
speaker: Margaret

qText: How about September for us too?
speaker: Henry

qText: Right. Shall we go into Ducie Street ourselves in September? Or shall we try to bounce Helen and Tibby into it? That s rather an idea. They are so unbusinesslike, we could make them do anything by judicious management. Look here--yes. We ll do that. And we ourselves could live at Howards End or Shropshire.
speaker: Margaret

qText: Heavens! how you women do fly round! My head s in a whirl. Point by point, Margaret. Howards End s impossible. I let it to Hamar Bryce on a three years  agreement last March. Don t you remember? Oniton. Well, that is much, much too far away to rely on entirely. You will be able to be down there entertaining a certain amount, but we must have a house within easy reach of Town. Only Ducie Street has huge drawbacks. There s a mews behind.
speaker: Henry

qText: Yes, in summer especially, the mews is a serious nuisance. The smoking-room, too, is an abominable little den. The house opposite has been taken by operatic people. Ducie Street s going down, it s my private opinion.
speaker: Henry

qText: How sad! It s only a few years since they built those pretty houses.
speaker: Margaret

qText: Shows things are moving. Good for trade.
speaker: Henry

qText: I hate this continual flux of London. It is an epitome of us at our worst--eternal formlessness; all the qualities, good, bad, and indifferent, streaming away--streaming, streaming for ever. That s why I dread it so. I mistrust rivers, even in scenery. Now, the sea--
speaker: Margaret

qText: High tide, yes.
speaker: Henry

qText: And these are the men to whom we give the vote,
speaker: Henry

qText: However, they have their own lives and interests. Let s get on.
speaker: Henry

qText: A nice beginning, if your aunt saw you slip in alone!
speaker: Henry

qText: But I always do go about alone. Considering I ve walked over the Apennines, it s common sense. You will make me so angry. I don t the least take it as a compliment.
speaker: Margaret

qText: It isn t meant as a compliment, my dear. I just won t have you going about in the dark. Such people about too! It s dangerous.
speaker: Henry

qText: Can t I look after myself? I do wish--
speaker: Margaret

qText: Come along, Margaret; no wheedling.
speaker: Henry

qText: Margaret
speaker: Henry
refExp: Mr Wilcox who was in front said

qText: You ve waked the baby. I knew you would. (Rum-ti-foo, Rackety-tackety-Tompkin!) I m not responsible for what Uncle Percy does, nor for anybody else or anything, so there!
speaker: Dolly

qText: Who asked him while I was away? Who asked my sister down to meet him? Who sent them out in the motor day after day?
speaker: Charles Wilcox

qText: Charles, that reminds me of some poem.
speaker: Dolly

qText: Does it indeed? We shall all be dancing to a very different music presently. Miss Schlegel has fairly got us on toast.
speaker: Charles Wilcox

qText: I could simply scratch that woman s eyes out, and to say it s my fault is most unfair.
speaker: Dolly

qText: It s your fault, and five months ago you admitted it.
speaker: Charles Wilcox

qText: I didn t.
speaker: Dolly

qText: You did.
speaker: Charles Wilcox

qText: Tootle, tootle, playing on the pootle!
speaker: Dolly

qText: It s all very well to turn the conversation, but father would never have dreamt of marrying as long as Evie was there to make him comfortable. But you must needs start match-making. Besides, Cahill s too old.
speaker: Charles Wilcox

qText: Of course, if you re going to be rude to Uncle Percy.
speaker: Dolly

qText: Miss Schlegel always meant to get hold of Howards End, and, thanks to you, she s got it.
speaker: Charles Wilcox

qText: I call the way you twist things round and make them hang together most unfair. You couldn t have been nastier if you d caught me flirting. Could he, diddums?
speaker: Dolly

qText: We re in a bad hole, and must make the best of it. I shall answer the pater s letter civilly. He s evidently anxious to do the decent thing. But I do not intend to forget these Schlegels in a hurry. As long as they re on their best behaviour--Dolly, are you listening?--we ll behave, too. But if I find them giving themselves airs or monopolising my father, or at all ill-treating him, or worrying him with their artistic beastliness, I intend to put my foot down, yes, firmly. Taking my mother s place! Heaven knows what poor old Paul will say when the news reaches him.

Neither you, nor I, nor my informant, nor the man who informed him, nor the directors of the Porphyrion, are to blame for this clerk s loss of salary. qText: You mean to keep proportion, and that s heroic, it s Greek, and I don t see why it shouldn t succeed with you. Go on and fight with him and help him. Don t ask me for help, or even for sympathy. Henceforward I m going my own way. I mean to be thorough, because thoroughness is easy. I mean to dislike your husband, and to tell him so. I mean to make no concessions to Tibby. If Tibby wants to live with me, he must lump me. I mean to love you more than ever. Yes, I do. You and I have built up something real, because it is purely spiritual. There s no veil of mystery over us. Unreality and mystery begin as soon as one touches the body. The popular view is, as usual, exactly the wrong one. Our bothers are over tangible things--money, husbands, house-hunting. But Heaven will work of itself.

qText: Mismanagement did it--besides, the days for small farms are over. It doesn t pay--except with intensive cultivation. Small holdings, back to the land--ah! philanthropic bunkum. Take it as a rule that nothing pays on a small scale. Most of the land you see

qText: belongs to the people at the Park--they made their pile over copper--good chaps. Avery s Farm, Sishe s--what they call the Common, where you see that ruined oak--one after the other fell in, and so did this, as near as is no matter.

qText: When I had more control I did what I could--sold off the two and a half animals, and the mangy pony, and the superannuated tools; pulled down the outhouses; drained; thinned out I don t know how many guelder-roses and elder-trees; and inside the house I turned the old kitchen into a hall, and made a kitchen behind where the dairy was. qText: Why didn t I begin with it? I have found out something about Mr. Wilcox. He has behaved very wrongly indeed, and ruined two people s lives. It all came on me very suddenly last night; I am very much upset, and I do not know what to do. Mrs. Bast--

qText: Shall I lock the door again?

qText: No thanks, Tibbikins. You re being very good to me. I want to tell you the story before I go abroad, you must do exactly what you like--treat it as part of the furniture. Meg cannot have heard it yet, I think. But I cannot face her and tell her that the man she is going to marry has misconducted himself. I don t even know whether she ought to be told. Knowing as she does that I dislike him, she will suspect me, and think that I want to ruin her match. I simply don t know what to make of such a thing. I trust your judgment. What would you do?

qText: I gather he has had a mistress,
speaker: Tibby

qText: And ruined two people s lives. And goes about saying that personal actions count for nothing, and there always will be rich and poor. He met her when he was trying to get rich out in Cyprus--I don t wish to make him worse than he is, and no doubt she was ready enough to meet him. But there it is. They met. He goes his way and she goes hers. What do you suppose is the end of such women?
speaker: Helen

qText: They end in two ways: Either they sink till the lunatic asylums and the workhouses are full of them, and cause Mr. Wilcox to write letters to the papers complaining of our national degeneracy, or else they entrap a boy into marriage before it is too late. She--I can t blame her.
speaker: Helen

qText: But this isn t all,
speaker: Helen

qText: I come now to the business that took us to Oniton. We went all three. Acting on Mr. Wilcox s advice, the man throws up a secure situation and takes an insecure one, from which he is dismissed. There are certain excuses, but in the main Mr. Wilcox is to blame, as Meg herself admitted. It is only common justice that he should employ the man himself. But he meets the woman, and, like the cur that he is, he refuses, and tries to get rid of them. He makes Meg write. Two notes came from her late that evening--one for me, one for Leonard, dismissing him with barely a reason. I couldn t understand. Then it comes out that Mrs. Bast had spoken to Mr. Wilcox on the lawn while we left her to get rooms, and was still speaking about him when Leonard came back to her. This Leonard knew all along. He thought it natural he should be ruined twice. Natural! Could you have contained yourself?
speaker: Helen

Feel the cellar walls; look up under the eaves. Ask Sir James or any one. Those Shropshire valleys are notorious. qText: I am obliged to question you on subjects we d both prefer to leave untouched. As you know, I am not one of your Bernard Shaws who consider nothing sacred. To speak as I must will pain me, but there are occasions--We are husband and wife, not children. I am a man of the world, and you are a most exceptional woman.
speaker: Henry

qText: I see that you feel as I felt when--My poor little wife! Oh, be brave! Just one or two questions, and I have done with you. Was your sister wearing a wedding-ring?

I could understand it if it was her old home, because a home, or a house,

qText: It is unreasonable, but the request of an unhappy girl. Tomorrow she will go to Germany, and trouble society no longer. Will you forgive her as you hope to be forgiven, and as you have actually been forgiven? Forgive her for one night only. That will be enough.
